  "text": "We returned to our electron microscopy images (Fig. 2) to measure vesicle diameters and compared them with those measured from capacitance (Fig. 7c,d ). Microvesicle diameters were very similar across methods and animals (electron microscopy yielded 36.3 ± 0.2 nm (n ¼ 868) for wild-type and 36.1 ± 0.3 (n ¼ 479) for knockout vesicles; P ¼ 0.25). The slightly larger electron microscopy values could be accounted for by a specific membrane capacitance that is slightly lower than the 0.9 mF cm -2 value 25 that we used in the conversion (such a small change is well within the tolerance of the measurement). In contrast, the disparity between electron microscopy and capacitance diameters was greater for DCVs (89.9 ± 0.5 nm (n ¼ 2,020) for wild-type and 106.7 ± 1.2 nm (n ¼ 635) for knockout terminals; P o 0.0001). Furthermore, the mean diameter of DCVs in the electron microscope was significantly greater in knockouts than in wild types. These differences are unlikely to reflect different values of the specific membrane capacitance of DCVs; a lower value could bring the numbers for DCV diameter in line for wild type or knockout, but not for both. Previous reports have also noted larger DCVs in the presence of elevated Syt IV levels [CITATION_1] , and the maturation of DCVs 27 offers a more satisfying explanation. Capacitance probably selects exocytosis-competent DCVs that are more mature and smaller. Because Syt IV functions in DCV maturation [CITATION_2] , knockout nerve terminals could contain a larger proportion of less mature and larger DCVs.",
